Кручу-верчу, запутать хочу!

Довольно скучный сборник головоломок, в которых игроку предстоит создать выход, или добраться до него - используя гравитацию. К огромному сожалению игра имеет ряд проблем, что делает прохождение игры - головной болью. Это и выпадение предметов за пределы карты, и возможность получить головокружение из-за постоянных сумбурных перемещений игрока в гравитационных полях, и баги - при которых Вы можете просто застрять в текстурах, или объектах на карте.

Тем не менее, не смотря на кажущуюся сложность - задачи быстро решаются. Главное понять возможности гравитации и - если игра уж очень сильно приелась - использовать разнообразнейшие глюки и гличи, что не были исправлены в течении трех лет "разработки".

Не смотря на проблемы я бы мог рекомендовать данный проект любителям головоломок. Но из-за жадности разработчика и не умения работать с региональными ценами - я не рекомендую тратить 30$ на игру, что стоит ( и стоила) всего несколько центов.

Суть: есть 18 уровней, чтобы пройти каждый, надо найти кубы и поставить их на кнопки. Сложность в том что везде инвертирована гравитация, и на каждом отсеке уровня в свою сторону, так что вычислить маршрут еще та задача. Easy платина

Небольшая головоломка с интересной механикой невесомости и гравитационных полей.
Все 18 уровней интересны. Однако сложность головоломок невысокая. Единственные трудности может вызвать изучение проектировки самих уровней. Ибо решать головоломки в трёхмерном пространстве всё-таки сложнее. Хоть в игре нет верха и низа, наш мозг всё равно продолжает мыслить стереотипными понятиями о локациях. И иногда перепрыгивая на потолок можно быстро потерять все привычные ориентиры. Но как только вы поняли планировку уровня, дальше решение идёт как по маслу.

Первые несколько уровней кажутся самыми замудрёнными и сложными. Но позже они становятся меньше и проще. Однако в целом геймдизайн у игры хороший. Я ожидала, что меня быстро стошнит с моей вестибуляркой. Однако необходимости часто вертеть камерой не было. Маршрут спокойно можно прокладывать в голове. А на экране достаточно хорошо видно большую часть локации целиком. Это определённо плюс, как мне кажется, для 3D головоломок. С такой задумкой очень легко можно было напортачить с уровнями.

Кстати, не знаю как тестилась игра, но иногда встречаются немного мешающие комфортно играть вещи. Не критичные, решаются рестартом уровня (если знаешь как, повторно пройти кусок уровня не сложно). Однако помимо этого некоторые уровни можно пройти явно не так, как это задумывалось разработчиками. Обходные пути и лазейки лежат прямо на поверхности.

Так что в целом игра проходится довольно быстро (в т.ч. на подсолнух). Пару часов играете в игру. Ещё часов 6 выбиваете остаток карточек.

Évaluation publiée le 29 juin 2021
This really feels like the first project someone actually completed, and then somehow was allowed to throw up on Steam for five bucks.

The "game" is just 18 levels on a level select screen (which is very broken - just try to hit 'next page' after you're already on the next page and watch the game freak out). The direction of gravity is denoted by "boxes" surrounding areas of gravity, with the sides of the box being depicted with moving lines - this works fine when you're viewing the "boxes" from the side, but from the top (where you're often viewing them) you get the same visual effect, even though it doesn't correspond to the direction of gravity at all. There's also no indication that there's a rewinding-time mechanic, which you activate by holding right mouse button (though it only really rewinds the discount Aperture Science Weighted Storage Cubes that populate every level). The buttons and switches also have a habit of breaking regularly and refusing to reactivate, requiring you to restart the level.

Each level is set within a featureless cube, and this is really where the gameplay starts to fall apart. The level itself has no color or texture, but the objects within it - walls, cubes, windows, etc - are surprisingly detailed. The game is aesthetically incoherent; it'd actually be better if the objects within the game were *less* detailed, and the gameplay itself made tighter - see the game QUBE for comparison. And, oh, does this gameplay need some tightening. Most levels start you next to a cube, which is a big mistake, because you can use the time mechanic to hop around the level pretty freely. You can also easily launch yourself at high speed in random directions, which is generally less useful. In fact, because the game is set within cubic levels, with areas usually partitioned by a pretty low wall, you can often jump over a lot of the walls you're clearly not supposed to; you tend to slide down them like slopes, presumably to prevent this, but for some reason you don't slide off while rewinding time, which you can do freely. Even without cubes, and even without rewinding time, because the areas of gravity are determined by these sloppily-placed "boxes," you can often walk along walls you aren't supposed to just because they made some gravity box too big or too small and they don't line up neatly with the walls. In fact, there were a few levels where I TRIED to solve them normally, and ended up jumping a bit too high and falling into the final section completely by accident.

I beat all the levels in just barely over an hour, and frankly the levels that I couldn't bypass were the most boring ones; I had a lot more fun finding ways to climb over walls than I did trying to reverse-engineer the developers' intent. At 90% off - a mere $0.49 - I feel like I got my money's worth, but I couldn't recommend this to anyone else.

Évaluation publiée le 14 novembre 2023
I don't want to mislead players into thinking that this is worth the 30€/$ it is asking for, so until the developer decides to change the price it's thumbs down from me. No I didn't buy it for the full price and you probably shouldn't either.

Review
An interesting concept, it is fun to jump in a room that has different gravitational fields. Like, I can walk on the ceiling or on the sides and it's fun. Some of the puzzles are pretty smart, but some others can be cheated because the levels aren't well made. I beat some of the levels by accident because the gravity fields were put in such a way that I flew to the " Exit " (The Exit is the end of the level). So that made me not care about finishing the level the way it was intended to be played.

The Tutorial is pretty much useless as it doesn't explain things properly. Most of my gameplay time was trying to figure out what certain buttons do or how to use time manipulation ( You have to hold right click and then the cube will warp back to its previous position ).

On a side note, I like the futuristic look of the levels and its relaxing soundtrack. The colors also contribute to the sci-fi look, but they may be too intense for some people's eyes. There are also some ray traced(?) reflections for some extra eye candy.

Évaluation publiée le 6 mai 2021
After playing the first two levels, feeling sea-sick afterwards, I decided that was enough for me.

In each level you start out in a giant cubic room with a lot of crap everywhere. There's computer boards you cannot interact with, energy generators that sparkle with no purpose, and lots of futuristic looking mumbo jumbo. Plus, there's tons of glowing sparkles, supposedly indicating gravity fields, that just get in the way of being able to see what's what. Every wall can be a floor, with six different gravity fields going every which way.

The underlying idea is conceptually simple, but in practice, it becomes sickening and nauseating when trying to navigate the room, falling in one random direction to the next. I felt like a piece of popcorn being tossed around in a popcorn maker.

At first, the goal of the room was unclear. I saw there were weight switches that need to be held down, but had no idea how. After quickly watching a video online--can't believe I had to, but the game was making me sick just playing it--I saw there were cubes to grab, which I had overlooked them amid the overwhelming chaos of the room.

Next I struggled with just placing a cube on a switch. Simple right? Not in this game. After a few frustrating minutes, I discovered you need to grab a cube pressing E and then place it also with E. If you make the mistake that I did of clicking the mouse instead of pressing E to release the cube, then the cube goes flying across the room. Why not just let the cube drop? Have no idea. At first, I thought there was a gravity field propelling the cube upwards from the switch, since I kept clicking the mouse button thinking I was placing the cube on the switch. But no, that wasn't it. I realized that I was not just the victim of weird gravity fields but also poorly designed controls.

Once, I finally understood how the game worked, the game and the two levels I played were trivial, albeit sickening. Having a real tutorial would have been nice, and not a snarky one-minute intro video telling you need to figure out stuff on your own.

I could have played longer, but I didn't the see the point playing a sucky game pretending to be clever, when in fact it's a chaotic mess.

For 4 quid, I can't recommend this game. I would recommend this game only for puzzlers or game breakers if it was cheaper, so ye... maybe get it on sale.

I completed this in about 90 minutes, and I actually "broke" more levels to reach the exit than I solved, only going back to have another look at a few of the ones that I broke. I spent probably under 3 minutes on most of the later levels after I got used to the physics and graphics because they are so easy to break. I still haven't tried to figure out how to complete some of the levels as expected, and I'm not sure I will ever bother.

The primary graphics of the game aren't bad. Playing on a 4k monitor at 1080p (the 4k option is broken) with AA on and most of the options turned up, the textures and objects look ok and it runs very smoothly. The problem with the graphics is the obnoxious moving walls of light indicating different gravity fields. I'm not really sure how they could've been made worse. If it wasn't for the horrible walls of light and broken 4k, I would rate the graphics as maybe above average.

Some of the "puzzles" are really bad, and it turns out that trying to break the levels is just as much, if not more, fun compared to completing them as the dev probably expected.

Also the menu interface is messy and kinda broken in places...

Again, if you like puzzles, or just like to figure out stuff and make your own solutions, then definitely get this game on sale. I got it for less than a pound, and I certainly don't regret it.

Not sure why this has so many positive reviews, because it feels positively unfinished!

Other reviews have already mentioned the line "Exit is was spawned" you see when you complete a level, the horrible motion-sickness you get from being tossed around by the gravity changing, and the tutorial being a 2 minute video with a text-to-speech narrator.

But I want to reiterate how confusing the whole game is. There's barely any indication of what the objects in each level are for, so it's like being thrown into the future with no clue what anything is. On top of that, the gravity fields that the game is named for are very translucent and hard to see, with a tiny arrow showing which direction they go. This is made worse by each level being small and cubical, as you often have to look through a field at another field behind it to try to figure out where to go.

Now you'd think that this would make the game really hard, but to be honest, half the levels can be cheesed by jumping up walls or using the fields to fly across the level straight into the goal, so I guess it balances out.

The game still sucks though, especially because I feel like I was scammed by the reviews. The ones comparing it to Portal have to be some kind of joke, surely.

Gravity Field, üstü veya altı olmayan nesnelere sahip bir uzay mantık bulmaca oyunu olarak tanımlanıyor. Oyun minimalist bir tarzda yapılmıştır ve seviyeler, belirli bir işlevi yerine getiren gerekli öğeleri içeren kübik odalardan oluşur. Oyunda yer alan bulmacaların çözümü için yerçekimi kavramı kullanılır. Her biri kendi yerçekimi yönüne sahip olan yerçekimi alanları vardır ve oyuncu bu alanlara girdiğinde yerçekimi kuvveti değişir. Ayrıca bazı bulmacalarda zamanı tersine çevirme simgesi de bulunur ve bazı öğeler için zamanın geri döneceği anlamına gelir.

Katlarda, açılımı belli olmayan kapalı kapılarla da karşılaşılır ve bu kapıları açmak için belirli öğeler kullanılır. Всем доброй ночи. Сегодня пишу обзор на игру, которая называеться Gravity Field.

Эта игра являеться небольшим таким амажем на Portal, потому что когда я запускал игру, то увидел что она из себя представляет, а сама игра в жанре головоломка.

Я очень люблю разгадывать загадки(если это конечно не ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ пятнашки, или не то что было в Cry of Fear).

Итак, вас игра встречает главным меню и вы просто нажимаете на первую попавшуюся карту, советую начать с первой, ну или на ваш выбор). В самой игре довольно много приколюх. Эти приколы вы увидите в местном Туториале, ну или когда будете сами всё лично проходить. Правда как я видел в "обучении", мужской голос чисто спойлернул некоторые карты, поэтому я этот раздел смотрел уже ПОСЛЕ прохождения), чисто ради интереса.

Музыка очень приятная, играет эмбинс. Очень расслабляет.

Интересный факт насчёт игры. Иногда я уровни проходил довольно быстро, а иногда я сидел в них минут 10-15, от силы.

Самое забавное это то, что иногда мой персонаж мог левитировать и я непонимал, это баг такой или так и было задумано. Я назвал этот приём "левитирующий лифт" .

Да, в игре есть лифт, но под лифтом я имею в виду не только средство передвижения, но и особый приём (его ещё использовали в далёком 2016, спидранеры Сталкера, когда эта игра бьла на пике популярности).

Подведя итог скажу, если вы любите загадки и скучаете по временам Портала и других подобных игр, то вам эту игру я рекомендую . Моя оценка 10 электро-шаров из 10.

Gravity Field

Ist ein gut aussehendes 3D Puzzlespiel...
Wo definitiv eure Logik abgefragt wird...
Ihr startet immer in einen Raum wo es kein Oben und Unten gibt...
Zu beginn müsst ihr ein Reaktor aktivieren dafür legt ihr auf jede Druckplatte ein Würfel.. und kommt somit zum Ziel.
Diese Aufgaben variieren von Level zu Level...
Das Grundprinzip bleibt aber gleich...
Ihr müsst durch Druckplatten verschiedene Lifte oder Tore aktivieren.. die euch zum Exit bringen.

Insgesamt gibt es leider nur 18 Level.
Immerhin gibt es dafür Errungenschaften und Steam Karten.

Wer ein bisschen Knobeln will und schwindelfrei ist kann sich gerne das Spiel mal zulegen..
Ich würde nur warten bis das Game im Sale ist da 30€ schon ein stolzer Preis ist.
(Ich habe es zum Glück umsonst bekommen)

Ansonsten viel Spaß damit
MFG Crow

Prepare yourself for an infuriating journey into the abyss of gaming disappointment with Gravity Field, a title that manages to defy expectations in all the wrong ways. I can't emphasize enough just how mind-numbingly frustrating this game turned out to be, leaving me questioning not only the choices made in its development but also the very nature of my decision to play it.

Let's start with the gameplay—a convoluted mess of poorly executed mechanics that seem to have been designed solely to induce rage. The concept of navigating through a gravity-altered environment might sound intriguing, but in reality, it's an exercise in sheer aggravation. The controls are clunky and unresponsive, turning every attempt at precision into an exercise in futility. You'll find yourself screaming at the screen as your character, seemingly guided by the forces of chaos, careens into obstacles and pitfalls with alarming regularity.

The level design in Gravity Field is a study in frustration. Each stage feels like a sadistic obstacle course, designed to crush any semblance of enjoyment. The difficulty curve is not a curve at all but a steep, unrelenting incline, making progress feel more like an exercise in luck than skill. It's as if the developers took pleasure in watching players suffer, with each new level presenting a fresh hell of infuriating challenges and absurdly placed hazards.

Graphics and visuals are a disappointment as well. Instead of immersing players in a visually engaging world, Gravity Field offers a bland and uninspired backdrop that does nothing to redeem the overall experience. It's a missed opportunity to create a captivating atmosphere that might have offered some solace in the face of the game's numerous shortcomings.

The soundtrack, or lack thereof, further contributes to the overall sense of mediocrity. A forgettable and repetitive loop of uninspired tunes does little to alleviate the frustration, leaving players with an audio experience that matches the lackluster quality of the rest of the game.

In conclusion, Gravity Field is a textbook example of how not to make a game. It's a masterclass in frustration, offering little in the way of entertainment or satisfaction. Save yourself the agony and avoid this game at all costs. There are countless other titles out there that respect your time and effort far more than this abysmal excuse for a gaming experience.

Évaluation publiée le 13 décembre 2023
"Gravity Field" by Kazakov Studios is an ambitious and mind-bending puzzle game that challenges players to navigate through gravity-defying environments. With its unique concept and engaging gameplay, it stands out as a captivating experience for puzzle enthusiasts.

Visually, the game shines with its sleek and futuristic design. The minimalist aesthetics complement the gravity-altering mechanics, allowing players to focus on the puzzles without unnecessary distractions. The environments are well-crafted, utilizing the manipulation of gravity to create intricate and thought-provoking challenges.

Gameplay-wise, "Gravity Field" excels in its innovative use of gravity as the core puzzle-solving mechanic. Players must strategically manipulate gravitational forces to navigate obstacles, reach checkpoints, and solve puzzles. The puzzles gradually increase in complexity, providing a satisfying level of challenge without becoming overly frustrating.

The game's soundtrack deserves commendation for enhancing the overall experience. The music complements the gameplay, creating an immersive atmosphere that adds to the game's allure.

However, "Gravity Field" is not without its minor flaws. Some players might find certain puzzles overly challenging, leading to occasional frustration. Additionally, while the game's mechanics are intriguing, it could benefit from additional variety in level design and puzzles to maintain long-term engagement.

Overall, "Gravity Field" is a standout puzzle game that offers a refreshing and stimulating experience. Its innovative gameplay mechanics, sleek visuals, and immersive soundtrack make it a compelling choice for puzzle enthusiasts seeking a unique challenge. Despite minor challenges, the game's strengths outweigh its weaknesses, making it a game that I highly recommend for those looking for a mentally engaging and enjoyable puzzle-solving experience.

グラフィックと音楽は良さそうなのですが、日本語非対応と書いてないにも関わらず、英語と他の言語のみの選択しかなく、かつフルスクリーンで遊べません。
解像度の設定などがありますが、1920ｘ1080と、なぜかワイド画面ではない3840ｐｘの解像度。しかも、4ｋの解像度にすると画面がバグってしまい、メニュー項目なども触れなくなります。（正確には位置がずれてしまう）
1080ｐでもフルスクリーン設定ができますが、ゲームを開始しようとすると強制的にウインドウモードになります。

ゲーム配信でも問題ない動作であれば試行錯誤する様子を配信しようと思いましたが、フルスクリーンモードにしていても、ＯＢＳでは画面の隅にしか映像が出なかったりなど、かなり勿体ない状態です。

ストーリーをつけてほしいとは思いませんが、チュートリアルが欲しいですね。
Portalや同種のゲームを色々やっていますが、それでも全く何をしていいのか分かりませんでした。
メインメニューにGuideというのがあるのですが、こちらも英語での説明なのですが、見てみた感じではやはり何をしていいのかが分かりませんでした。

グラフィックも音楽も良さそうなので、上記の部分の修正に期待ですね。現時点では残念としか言いようがないです

"Gravity Field" ist ein Indie-Spiel, das von SoerGame und Kazakov Studios entwickelt und von Kazakov Studios veröffentlicht wurde. Es wurde am 13. Oktober 2020 veröffentlicht und kann seit dem 6. Oktober 2020 im Early Access gespielt werden.

Das Spiel bietet eine interessante Spielmechanik, bei der die Spieler mit der Schwerkraft spielen und ihre Umgebung manipulieren müssen, um Rätsel zu lösen. Die Grafiken sind gut gestaltet und die Steuerung ist einfach zu verstehen.

Es gibt jedoch auch einige Dinge, die verbessert werden könnten. Einige Spieler berichten, dass das Spiel etwas kurz ist und dass es schwierig ist, das Interesse aufrechtzuerhalten.

Insgesamt ist "Gravity Field" ein unterhaltsames Spiel, das besonders für Spieler geeignet ist, die auf der Suche nach einem einfachen, aber unterhaltsamen Spiel sind, bei dem sie mit der Schwerkraft spielen können. Es ist jedoch wichtig zu beachten, dass es einige Schwächen hat, die es von einem großartigen Spiel abhalten.

Seriously ! This game is really making me think. Not only understanding how to navigate the gravity fields in 3 dimensional planes but also the insanity of the Time Reversal mechanic on the right mouse click. This really is a very challenging concept to understand having the ability to reverse time and thus where the cubes are...or were...when you need to be someplace else when the reversed time gets to the right point. I cant really explain it but its twisting my brain in my skull. As of writing this, I have got to level 6 and pondering life trying to imagine time reversal steps before I actually commence. If you want a brain twister with minimal/no guidance or hand holding then go for it. This is the first puzzle game that I have played with a Time Reversal mechanic and I think my head is going to explode !
Edit..the Time Reversal mechanic definitely needs to be developed more in new levels as the potential for real mind bending levels could be so much more used as a key game aspect. It feels like it was under used, but I can understand why as its a real head scratcher to solve let alone build/code level designs for it. Hope the dev can do more with it.
